<br>
If a guild wants/needs to invite other people along on their kill, that is their right.  It shouldn't matter if they are alliances, friends, total strangers.  The way I see it, at this time the only way for me and my guild to get any experience in how to attempt these dragons is to be invited along with someone else.  We aren't quite ready to take these on our own, and some of my members are a bit impatient for their drops.  So if they can go along with another guild, even if we don't know the guild ahead of time, I think that is great.  Besides giving us experience on the dragons it also gives us a chance to interface with other guilds and make more friends in the process.<br>
<br>
Now I know you have said time and again that you guys are willing to take other people with you, and that you are willing to help others learn how you take these dragons out.  That is great, I'm glad you are willing to do this.  Perhaps I can draw upon your expertise when my raid officers think we're ready to be added to the rotation.  And perhaps I'll send you a tell to find out when you're planning to take them down and see if anyone in my guild would be able to go along.  It seems you don't mind getting tells; I don't really like to bother people I don't know without &quot;permission&quot; so to speak (which public postings saying &quot;we need help with naggy&quot; give me, I feel).<br>
<br>
But if you think about it, how did you guys learn your techniques?  Did someone teach you or did you try and fail several times before you got it down?  If someone taught you, who taught them?  Somewhere along the line, there was much death at the feet of these foul beasts before the perfect method was established.  If someone else wishes to take the same road in their learning curve, that is up to them.<br>
